Turkey's August 1999 earthquake with 7.4 magnitude was its largest since 1976 and first in Turkey's densely populated industrial west.
Over 12,000 were dead, 45,000 injured, and 35,000 missing.
Over 100,000 buildings were destroyed, partly due to shoddy construction and lax regulation.
Bridges, highways, power stations, and water and telephone lines were damaged.
Turkey's largest oil refinery burned and the Golcuk naval base was destroyed.
Hundreds of thousands were homeless.
Disease was feared.
Economic damage ran to $20 billion.
Countries worldwide sent money, relief workers and equipment.
Turkish rescue efforts were plagued by inexperience, poor organization and lack of supplies.
